    <h2 id="why-vitamin-c">Why Vitamin C Matters for Children's Immune Health</h2>

    <p>Vitamin C (ascorbic acid) is an essential water-soluble nutrient that plays a central role in immune function, collagen synthesis, iron absorption, and antioxidant defense. Children cannot produce vitamin C internally — it must be obtained through diet or supplementation. While citrus fruits and vegetables are the best dietary sources, picky eaters often fall short of the recommended daily intake, making supplementation a practical strategy for maintaining optimal immune function throughout the school year and cold and flu season.</p>

