    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Vitamin C Gummies for Kids</h2>

    <details class="fq"><summary>How much vitamin C do kids need daily?</summary><p>The NIH recommends 15mg for ages 1-3, 25mg for ages 4-8, 45mg for ages 9-13, and 65-75mg for ages 14-18. Most kids' gummies provide 60-250mg, which is safe and within tolerable upper limits (400mg for ages 1-3, 650mg for ages 4-8, 1,200mg for ages 9-13).</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Can vitamin C help kids get sick less often?</summary><p>A 2013 Cochrane review of 29 trials found daily vitamin C supplementation reduced cold duration by 14% in children. It did not prevent colds but reduced their severity. The benefit requires consistent daily supplementation before illness onset.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>What form of vitamin C is best for kids?</summary><p>Ascorbic acid is the most studied and bioavailable form. Sodium ascorbate is gentler on sensitive stomachs. Whole-food sources like amla berry and acerola cherry provide vitamin C with natural bioflavonoids, though clinical evidence does not show superior efficacy at equivalent doses.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Can kids take too much vitamin C?</summary><p>Very high doses can cause diarrhea and nausea, but vitamin C is water-soluble and excess is excreted in urine. Most kids' gummies provide well below the tolerable upper limits. Ensure multiple supplement sources do not combine to exceed the UL.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Should kids take vitamin C with zinc for immune support?</summary><p>Yes, combining vitamin C with zinc provides complementary immune benefits. Vitamin C enhances immune cell function while zinc supports immune cell development. Several products in our evaluation combine both nutrients effectively.</p></details>

    <details class="fq"><summary>Are vitamin C gummies as effective as chewable tablets?</summary><p>Yes, both deliver the same bioavailable ascorbic acid. Gummies offer better compliance — children take them more consistently, which is what drives immune benefits according to research. The trade-off is slightly more sugar and calories.</p></details>

